>>63920468
>It was an infamous improvement in industrial efficiency when it came to making steel.
Right. Prior to the Bessemer Process, steel was an expensive material. If you bought a hatchet, even a high-quality one would have a wrought-iron head with a little sliver of steel welded into it for the cutting edge. The Bessemer Process allowed for things like breech-loading artillery to be practical. In a setting where ferrous metallurgy exists, and steel is known, a faction or group that figures out that you can purify steel by pumping air through the molten metal until it stops flaring and flaming, then add carbon to adjust its carbon content afterwards, is either going to get very very rich very very fast--Bessemer became, by current standards, Bill Gates level rich from licensing his invention--or conquer all its neighbors. The two aren't mutually exclusive. It's the sort of thing that changes the world.

Also, again, not trying to be a dick, but it seems like this species isn't very good at working together in more than tiny groups. Any group of competitors--it could be a different sapient species, or it could be a group that arises with different cultural norms, maybe with some very subtle mutation affecting temperament and behavioral tendencies--that comes along that is better at large-scale cooperation, is going to eat their lunch in a single generation.
